Friendly Neighborhood Mercenary - Elitists and Vagrants</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=arleanna>Arleanna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>WERE YOU NOT<br>ENTERTAINED?!</span><br>  Posts: 859<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/12/02 4:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.verizon.net/~vze4zjqg/EQ/Sphynx5.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: PS2 Vs. Xbox</span><hr size=1> I've never heard of an Xbox crashing, but I guess it could happen since I believe it uses the win2k kernal. From what I've seen, Xbox has much better graphics and sound than PS2. If you have a dolby digital 5.1 system and an HDTV you can get an HD upgrade for nicer graphics and an AV upgrade for digital fiber optic output. Games like splinter cell are amazing with 5.1 sound and HD output. Blows away any PC game. And at $199 it's much cheaper than any PC system you can buy. <br>
<br>
I haven't fooled around with Xbox live very much, although I do subcribe to it. It's a great concept if you think about it. Everyone you play against is garanteed to have DSL/Cable and a headset that plugs into the control pad so you can communicate while playing the game. I've heard my freinds at work rave about Ghost recon, mech assult, and unreal tournament on Xbox live. The Medal of Honor port to Xbox supports Xbox live also. The PC MOH game was awesome but I always wished that everyone on my team would have something like roger wilco. Well, with Xbox live you know everyone will.<br>
<br>
Also, the Xbox's DVD playback blows away PS2 (and many low to mid range DVD players for that matter), again with 5.1 digital fiber optic output.<br>
<br>
The Xbox also has a built in harddrive for storing games, MP3s, or game upgrades and updates using Xbox live. I have a ton of MP3s stored on my harddrive so when I play a game that would normally take the crappy music off the CD you can tell it to play the MP3s from the harddrive instead.<br>
<br>
Of course, the bigest downfall of Xbox is all the money you have to spend to get the amazing graphics, sound, and multiplayer connectivity. The Xbox is $199, the DVD controller is $27, the AV upgrade is $20, HD upgrade is $20, and Xbox live multiplayer support is $50 a year. Plus you have to have ethernet broadband like DSL/Cable/T3 or it wont work. Of course, to get the best sound and picture you need a dolby digital recever, 5 channel speaker system, subwoofer, and of course the HDTV. All of which can run from a couple thousand to tens of thousands. But when you're sneaking around in the dark paying splnter cell you will have the best gaming experience possible. Its hard to describe just how amazing the Xbox is when its used to its full potential.<br>
<br>
If you are on a limited budget, don't have broadband, and don't give a shit about how good the games sound or look then buy the one that has more of the games you like. Athough Xbox still wins if you take into account the multiplayer support, faster Nvidia graphics card and CPU, the  internal harddrive, and better CD-R and DVD play back.<br>
<br>
I play on my friend's PS2 sometimes and although I do like some PS2 games that aren't available on Xbox I'm very unimpressed by the overall gaming experience on the PS2. As more Xbox units are sold more game designers will jump on the Xbox bandwagon. The original $299 price convinced many designers that Xbox would be a loser. But at $199 it's no more expensive than the inferior PS2.<br>
<br>
<br>
Edit: By the way, gamecube is for kids who like Mario Brothers, Pokemon, and gay animae games.<br>
